  "prompt": "Is O-ve universal donor?",
  "response": "Yes, O-negative (O-) blood is considered the universal donor type for red blood cells. This means that individuals with O- blood can donate their red blood cells to patients of any blood type without causing an incompatible reaction. This is particularly important in emergency situations where there may not be time to determine a patient's blood type. However, it's important to note that while O- can donate red blood cells universally, other components of blood, such as plasma and platelets, do have specific compatibility requirements.",
